The study, Salud en El Rosal, reveals that parents with children or unborn babies in El Rosal experience varying levels of stress, but through generating specific communication strategies, they can mitigate it and achieve well-being.

This study identifies knowledge, attitudes, and provider practices relevant to childhood pertussis infection (whooping cough) among healthcare workers and parents in Honduras. Read the full secondary study

In order to fully understand the journey of a patient acquiring the HPV Vaccine, the PATH research team completed an ethnographic study to investigate facilitators and barriers to patient access, education, and provider education in Arkansas and Indiana.

In 2013, the Quest Diagnostics Sexually Transmitted Disease (STD) Testing Business embarked on a project to increase awareness of and demand for STI testing in the United States. As part of this project, Quest commissioned a nationally-representative survey of sexually active Americans between the ages of 18 and 75.

This study produced a comprehensive assessment of vaccine-related behavior and knowledge among a sample of women aged 16–44 living in 18 low- and middle-income countries — including Brazil, Egypt, India, Mexico, Nigeria, South Africa, and Vietnam.
